title: ICE when passing incorrect parameter to `Path::from`

labels.name: I-ICE
labels.description: Issue: The compiler panicked, giving an Internal Compilation Error (ICE) ❄️

labels.name: T-compiler
labels.description: Relevant to the compiler team, which will review and decide on the PR/issue.

body:
### Code ```Rust use std::path::Path; fn main() { let p = Path::from(format!("hello")); } ``` I haven't found this ICE to occur when doing either of: ``` let p = Path::from("hello"); let p = Path::from(String::from("hello")); ``` ### Meta The bug does not exist on `rustc 1.64.0-nightly (fe3342816 2022-08-01)`. `rustc --version --verbose`: ``` rustc 1.65.0 (897e37553 2022-11-02) binary: rustc commit-hash: 897e37553bba8b42751c67658967889d11ecd120 commit-date: 2022-11-02 host: aarch64-apple-darwin release: 1.65.0 LLVM version: 15.0.0 ``` ### Error output ``` error: internal compiler error: compiler/rustc_middle/src/ty/context.rs:703:13: node_type: no type for node `expr { let res = $crate::fmt::format($crate::__export::format_args!($($arg)*)); res } (hir_id=HirId { owner: DefId(0:6 ~ splash_todo[9f65]::main), local_id: 30 })` thread 'rustc' panicked at 'Box', /rustc/897e37553bba8b42751c67658967889d11ecd120/compiler/rustc_errors/src/lib.rs:1462:9 stack backtrace: 0: 0x10562f670 -
